                     <interp inst="def2-2231-18360919" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">ELIZABETH REVELL</hi>
                  </persName> were in<lb></lb>dicted for<rs id="t18360919-2231-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18360919-2231-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18360919-2231-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> stealing, on the <rs id="t18360919-cd-183" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360919-2231-offence-1 t18360919-cd-183"></join>19th of September</rs>, 3 bottles, value 9<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; and 1 1/2 pint of wine, value 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18360919-name-1218" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18360919-name-1218" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360919-name-1218" type="surname" value="GREGORY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360919-name-1218" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360919-2231-offence-1 t18360919-name-1218"></join>John Gregory</persName>, their master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN GREGORY</hi>. I live in Newington-causeway, and am an oilman. The prisoners were my servants—Pearce was my porter, and Revell a ser<lb></lb>vant in the house—I have lost some bottles, and a pint and a half of wine—this is the wine and bottles—I sell British wines—the value of this is 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., bottles and all—they were found on the prisoner Pearce, in my pre<lb></lb>sence—from what he told me, I questioned Revell when she came in—she, after some time acknowledged that she ran down and drew the wine the moment I sat down to dinner, brought it up in a jug, and asked Pearce to get the bottles, which he did, and she filled them with wine, for him to take it home—she said she had never done so before—but in a short time she said she did it once before, when I was bottling a cask of wine, Pearce told her it was very good, and she said she had got him some—this led to other things—I had her sister's house searched, and some of my property was found, which was given up before the Magistrate—I will take Pearce into my service again.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360919-name-1219" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360919-name-1219" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360919-name-1219" type="surname" value="MORRIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360919-name-1219" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM MORRIS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 93.) On Monday last I was on duty, and saw Pearce putting some bottles into his pocket—I took him with these—I took him to his master, who identified the property.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Revell's Defence.</hi> Pearce came to me, and said his master was bottling some wine, and he should like to taste some—I went down and drew some—I brought it up and tasted it, it was very good—he said I durst not drink—I said, "Get a bottle;" and it would not hold all—he fetched another, and that was filled, and then the third.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Pearce.</hi> She gave it to me to take home to my sister, who was very ill.</p>
               <p>
